      "id": "emfo",
      "code_hash": "45fa74b137919676c7a02150c320d7a7",
      "outputs": [
        {
          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><h2 id=\"wiring-up-steam-input\">Wiring up Steam Input</h2>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">On the Deck (or any Steam controller paired with a desktop):</span>\n<ol>\n<li>Switch the Deck to <strong>desktop mode</strong> and open Steam.</li>\n<li>Open <strong>Settings \u2192 Controller</strong> and make sure Steam Input is enabled\n   for the active layout.</li>\n<li>Edit the layout for your browser (or use a global layout). The\n   <strong>d-pad</strong> is the obvious fit here \u2014 bind it to the four arrow keys\n   (most default desktop layouts already do this) and the accept /\n   fail / previous / defer actions just work. Bind a spare button \u2014\n   e.g. one of the back grips \u2014 to <strong>spacebar</strong> for voice notes.</li>\n<li>Open this notebook in the Deck's browser, click the annotation\n   widget once to give it focus, and start labeling.</li>\n</ol>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">Use Section 1 above any time you're unsure which key a given button is\nemitting.</span></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    }
